  "prompt": "What is colour of water?",
  "response": "Water itself is actually colorless and transparent. When you look at a small amount of water, it appears clear. However, when water is in large quantities, like in oceans, lakes, or swimming pools, it can appear to have different colors:\n\n1. Blue: Large bodies of water often look blue because water molecules absorb and scatter colors in sunlight, with red wavelengths being absorbed more and blue wavelengths being scattered.\n\n2. Green: Water can look green due to algae, minerals, or other substances in the water.\n\n3. Gray or Brown: These colors can result from sediment, pollution, or other particles in the water.\n\nBut in its pure, natural state, water is colorless and transparent.",
